AHB Protocol using Verilog HDL
Project Title

AHB-Lite Bus Protocol Implementation using Verilog HDL

Objective

The objective of this project is to implement a simple AHB-Lite bus protocol using Verilog HDL. The design demonstrates communication between an AHB Master and an AHB Slave using read and write operations.

Introduction

AHB (Advanced High-performance Bus) is part of the ARM AMBA architecture. It is a high-speed bus used to connect processors, memories, and peripherals in embedded systems. This project provides a basic implementation of an AHB Master, AHB Slave, and a Testbench for simulation purposes.

Project Files
File Name	Description
ahb_master.v	Implements the AHB Master
ahb_slave.v	Implements the AHB Slave
ahb_tb.v	Testbench for simulation
README.md	Project description
Features
Simple AHB-Lite implementation
Write operation
Read operation
32-bit Address Bus
32-bit Data Bus
Memory-based slave
Simulation testbench included
Bus Signals
Signal	Description
HCLK	System Clock
HRESETn	Active-Low Reset
HADDR	Address Bus
HWDATA	Write Data
HRDATA	Read Data
HWRITE	Read/Write Control
HTRANS	Transfer Type
HREADY	Ready Signal
HRESP	Response Signal
Working
Write Operation
Master sends an address.
Master places data on the write data bus.
HWRITE is set to logic '1'.
Slave stores the data in memory.
Read Operation
Master sends the address.
HWRITE is set to logic '0'.
Slave reads data from memory.
Slave sends data on the HRDATA bus.
Simulation Steps
Compile all Verilog files.
Start simulation.
Apply reset.
Perform write operation.
Perform read operation.
Verify the read data.
Expected Output
Write Address : 0x00000004
Write Data    : AABBCCDD

Read Address  : 0x00000004
Read Data     : AABBCCDD
Software Used
Verilog HDL
ModelSim / QuestaSim
Xilinx Vivado (Optional)
Conclusion

This project successfully demonstrates a basic implementation of the AHB-Lite protocol in Verilog. The Master and Slave communicate correctly through read and write transactions. This project is suitable for learning the fundamentals of the AHB protocol and can be extended with advanced features such as burst transfers, multiple masters, and bus arbitration.

